1. e4 e6 { The defining move of the French Defense. Moves like ...e5 and ...c5 immediately fight for space in the center by taking control of the d4. The French Defense, on the other hand, attempts to challenge white's central pawn structure with ...e6 followed by ...d5. } 2. d4 (2. d3 { The King's Indian Attack. This move is generally followed by Nd2, g3, Bg2, etc. White will aim for a kingside attack. Black can play ...d5 or transpose into a Sicilian with ...c5. } { [%cal Gc7c5,Gd7d5] })  (2. Nf3 d5 3. e5 c5 4. b4 { The Wing Gambit, White sacrifices a pawn in order to gain more control over the d4 square. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gc5d4] } 4... cxb4 5. d4)  (2. f4 { The La Bourdonnais Variation. White is usually planning on playing d4, but not until it is fully prepared. This way he has more time to get ready for the pressure on d4. }) 2... d5 { Black strikes out in the center, challenging white's e4 pawn. Here white has 4 main options. } 3. e5 { White immediately breaks the tension in the center while gaining space. Now that the center is locked, black can start attacking white's central pawn chain with ...c5, ...Nc6, often ...Qb6, and sometimes ...f6. } { [%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Gc7c5,Gb8c6,Gd8b6,Gf7f6] } (3. Nc3 { White's most aggressive option. White keeps the tension in the center by defending his e4 pawn. Black can indirectly attack the e4 pawn with ...Bb4, or directly attack it with ...Nf6. } { [%cal Gf8b4,Gg8f6] } 3... Bb4 { Here we have the Winawer variation: a sharp, tactical, and often aggressive variation. Black is prepared to give up his good dark-squared bishop in exchange for damaging white's pawn structure. It tremendously weakens the kingside, however, so white will often have a strong kingside attack. } { after 3...Bb4 , white can play a3 immediately leads in interesting position hope u like it } { [%csl Gg7,Ge4][%cal Gb4e1,Gc3e4] } (3... Nf6 { This is a simpler and more strategic alternative to the Winawer. Black pressures white's center directly. White has two options. } { [%cal Ge4e5,Gc1g5] } 4. e5 { White closes the center with a gain of tempo. Black will now attack white's central pawn chain with typical moves like ...c5, ...Nc6, ...Qb6, ...f6. } { [%cal Gf6d7,Gc7c5,Gb8c6,Gd8b6,Gf7f6] } (4. Bg5 { White takes pressure off of e4 by pinning the knight that was attacking it. This is one of white's most aggressive ways to play. It will often involve a kingside attack. Black has 3 main options. } { [%cal Gf8e7,Gf8b4,Gd5e4] } 4... Be7 { Black simply breaks the pin. White will close the center with e5, and black will be able to attack the center, but he must exchange his good bishop. } (4... Bb4 { The MacCutcheon Variation. Black puts even more pressure on e4 by pinning white's knight. This move leads to somewhat tactical positions, but they are far more positional than the Winawer. (Black responds to e5 with ...h6. White cannot win a piece). } { [%cal Ge4e5,Gh7h6] })  (4... dxe4 { The Burn Variation. The positions arising after this move are quite different from typical French positions. Black accepts doubled f-pawns for dynamic compensation. } 5. Nxe4 Be7 6. Bxf6 gxf6 { Black can make use of the semi-open g-file. The cluster of pawns on e6, f6, and f7 can often become very powerful as they can potentially control a lot of squares in the center. } { [%csl Gf6,Gf7,Ge6][%cal Gh8g8,Gg8g1,Gc7c5] })))  (3... dxe4 { This is the Rubinstein (or the Fort Knox if black plays ...Bc8-d7-c6). Black accepts a potentially passive position with less space, but obtains a solid position. } { [%cal Gc7c6,Gb8d7,Gg8f6,Gf8e7,Gf8d6] } 4. Nxe4 Bd7 { This is the Fort Knox Variation, where black spends time to bring his light-squared bishop out and, at the right moment, trades it for (usually) a white knight on f3. } { [%cal Gd7c6,Gc6f3] }) 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 dxe4 6. Qg4 Nf6 7. Qxg7 Rg8 8. Qh6)  (3. Nd2)  (3. exd5) *


