1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 { Normally in this position, White supports his central pawn chain with c3, but there is another interesting idea for White. One of Nimzowitsch's key concepts in "My System" is overprotection. In the two following lines, White sacrifices the d4 pawn in order to over protect e5, which can become sort of a wedge in White's position. } 3... c5 4. Nf3 { Rather than support the pawn chain as usual with c3, White simply develops a piece while defending d4. } 4... cxd4 { Since White didn't support the central pawn chain, Black can simply remove the base of it. Now White's e5 pawn is weaker. } { [%csl Ge5] } 5. Bd3 { If White simply takes back with the knight, Black will be a little better, so he instead blocks the pawn while developing a piece and preparing to castle. } 5... Nc6 { Black can develop, defend the d4 pawn, and put pressure on White's e5 pawn. } { [%cal Gc6d4,Gc6e5] } 6. O-O { Now the rook may be able to go to e1, where it supports e5. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gf1e1,Ge1e5] } 6... Nge7 { The knight is heading to g6, where it attacks White's e5 pawn. } 7. Bf4 { Since a knight on g6 will control the f4 square, now is White's only chance to play Bf4, where the bishop can support the e5 pawn. } { [%cal Gf4e5] } 7... Ng6 { [%cal Gg6e5,Gg6f4] } 8. Bg3 { Both sides are fighting for control of the e5 pawn. The winner of the battle will have a clear advantage. } { [%cal Gg6e5,Gc6e5,Gf3e5,Gg3e5] } 8... Bc5 { This bishop defends the d4 pawn, but the main purpose of this move is to reroute the bishop to c7, where it attacks e5. } { [%cal Gc5b6,Gb6c7,Gc7e5] } 9. Nbd2 { The knight is heading to g3, where it attacks d4. Once White has control of e5, he would like to land a piece on d4. } { [%cal Gd2b3,Gb3d4] } 9... Bd7 { This is a developing move, but it also allows the queen to go to b8, where it can attack e5 (c7 is occupied by the bishop). } { [%cal Gc5b6,Gb6c7,Gd8b8,Gb8e5] } 10. Nb3 { Another common idea is to play a3, b4, and at some point b5, to kick black's knight on c6 away and gain more control of e5. } { [%cal Gb3d4] } 10... Bb6 { The bishop was attacked and is heading to c7 anyway. } { [%cal Gb6c7] } 11. h4 { White is ready to play h5, attacking white's knight and decreasing black's control of e5. } { [%cal Gh4h5,Gg6e5,Gh5g6] } 11... Bc7 { [%cal Gc7e5] } 12. Re1 { [%cal Ge1e5] } 12... Qb8 { [%cal Gb8e5] } 13. Qe2 { In this position, both sides have almost all of their pieces aimed at e5, but it looks like White is winning. Because White has overprotected e5, it will become an irremovable wedge in Black's position. ...f6 will not be good for Black because White has too much control of e5 (and d4), and Black will remain cramped. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Ge1e5,Ge2e5,Gf3e5,Gg3e5,Gg6e5,Gc6e5,Gc7e5,Gb8e5,Gh4h5] } 13... a5 { This move was a mistake. Attacking the knight on b3 is useless since White is going to take on d4 anyway. This move gains space on the queenside, but is not the most effective way to do so. } 14. Nbxd4 { White regains his pawn and sets up an effective blockade on d4. } 14... Nxd4 15. Nxd4 Ne7 { This knight is best placed on c6 and was going to be kicked back to e7 by h5 from White. } { [%cal Ge7c6] } 16. h5 { White plays h5 anyway. This move is still useful as it gains space on the kingside. } 16... Qa7 { Black lost the battle for e5, so now he attempts to get White off of d4. } { [%cal Ga7d4] } 17. Qg4 { This move defends d4 and puts pressure on g7 (Qxg7 is not a good move yet, but putting pressure on g7 is still useful). } { [%cal Gg4g7,Gg4d4] } 17... Bb6 { Black attacks d4 again, but it is useless. } { [%cal Gb6d4] } 18. c3 Bxd4 19. cxd4 { At this point White is clearly better. White has the bishop pair, a strong central pawn chain, more space, and more active pieces. White overprotected e5 and maintained control over d4, which prevented Black from achieving any sort of counterplay whatsoever. } 19... Nc6 20. Qxg7 O-O-O 21. Bxh7 Qxd4 22. h6 Rdf8 23. Rad1 Qb4 24. a3 Qe7 25. Rc1 Kb8 *


