{ In this chapter I will share a very interesting novelty by Sergey Volkov in the French Defense. He has played this move only twice, and won both games. I will not spend too much time explaining the moves leading up to the novelty; I will focus mainly on the move itself and the moves following. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Bb4 { This is the defining move of the MacCutcheon variation. By pinning the knight, Black is indirectly attacking e4. In doing so, he is provoking White to play e5, thus closing the center and reaching the typical French Defense pawn structure. } 5. e5 h6 { at 6th instead of Bd2 white can also play exf6 and can reach in interesting line....... } 6. Bd2 (6. exf6 hxg5 7. fxg7 Rg8 8. h4 gxh4 9. Qg4 Qf6 10. Rxh4 Qxg7 11. Rh8 (11. Qxg7 Rxg7 12. Rh8+ Bf8)) 6... Bxc3 7. bxc3 Ne4 8. Qg4 { [%cal Gg4g7] } 8... Kf8 { [%cal Gf8g7] } 9. Bd3 { [%cal Gd3e4] } 9... Nxd2 10. Kxd2 c5 11. h4 { [%cal Gh1h3,Gh3f3,Gh4h5] } 11... Nc6 12. Rh3 { [%cal Gh3f3,Gf3f7] } 12... c4 13. Bf1 { [%cal Gg1e2,Ge2f4] } 13... Rg8 { This move has only been played twice (both by Sergey Volkov), and has a simple idea: to defend the g7 pawn and allow the king to escape to the queenside. } 14. Ne2 { White continues as normal and prepares the kingside attack. He does not realize, however, that the black king will be long gone by the time the attack is ready. } { [%cal Ge2f4,Gf4h5] } 14... Ke7 { Black begins the king-march to the queenside. } 15. Nf4 { [%cal Gf4h5] } 15... Qf8 { Black defends the f7 pawn and vacates the d8 square for the king. } { [%cal Gf8f7] } 16. Rf3 { With the king on the queenside, Black can try to obtain counterplay on the kingside. } { [%cal Gf3f8] } (16. Be2 { Now that the knight is on f4, the bishop can go to e2. This allows the rook on a1 to be involved in the attack. But this idea is still too slow. } { [%cal Ga1h1] } 16... Kd8 17. Nh5 { [%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5] } 17... Bd7 18. Qf4 { Rather than play for f4 and f5, white is going to thrust his g-pawn forward. } { [%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5] } 18... Kc7 19. g4 Qa3 { Black's king is safe for now, but a successful kingside attack by White will still be extremely dangerous, so he starts his counterplay on the queenside. } 20. Qe3 { White is spending too much time maneuvering. He is now preparing f4 and f5. } { [%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5] } 20... b5 { A common move for Black in these types of positions. ...b4 is coming. } { [%cal Gb5b4] } 21. f4 Rab8 { With the b-file about to be opened, Black gets his rook on an ideal square. } 22. Rhh1 { White intends to go Rf1 and support the f5 push. Also, this allows him to meet ...Qb2 with Rhb1. } 22... a5 23. Rhf1 { [%cal Gf1f5,Gf4f5] } 23... b4 { Finally Black is able to effectively play ...b4. } 24. f5 { With Black's queenside play progressing quickly, White needs to get his play on the kingside going. } 24... Qb2 25. Rfb1 { White's rook is now forced to leave the f-file. } 25... Qa3 { Here we have a position in which both sides have a lot of play. Black's king is not nearly as vulnerable as it was on f8, which gives him extra time to gain queenside counterplay. }) 16... Kd8 17. a4 { With this move, White temporarily prevents ...b5, giving himself more time for his kingside play. The problem with this is that, with Black's king on the queenside, Black can get his own counterplay on the kingside with ...f6. } { [%cal Gf7f6] } 17... Bd7 18. g3 { [%cal Gf1h3] } 18... Kc7 19. Bh3 Qe7 { [%cal Ga8f8] } 20. Ng2 { This move is not very good either. White is planning to bring the knight to e3, but on that square it does nothing except prepare f5, which is way too slow. } { [%cal Gg2e3] } 20... Raf8 { This move supports ...f6 and allows the king to go to the back rank without disconnecting the rooks. } { [%cal Gf7f6,Gc7c8] } 21. Ne3 Kc8 22. Qf4 f6 { With the king on the queenside, Black is free to counterattack on the kingside. With the typical French Defense pawn break, Black chips away at White's center and opens the f-file. } { [%cal Gf8f1,Gf6e5] } 23. exf6 Rxf6 24. Qg4 Rxf3 25. Qxf3 Rf8 { White has lost any chances of a kingside attack. Black now more active and slightly better. } { [%cal Gf8f2,Ge6e5,Gd7h3] } *


