{ With this move, White doesn't want the symmetrical pawn structure typically associated with the French Exchange, and instead opts for an IQP position. The most common reply to c4 is ...Nf6, after which we reach a typical IQP position. This is perfectly fine for Black, but there is one uncommon move that I prefer in this position. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. c4 Nc6 { This move at first doesn't make much sense, as it does nothing to help control the d5 square. It seems as though white can simply take on d5 and gain tempi on the queen. But, Black's knight is attacking d4, which creates some interesting options after cxd5. This position is a hybrid of the Chigorin Defense (1. d5 d5 2. c4 Nc6) and the French Exchange, and is a great surprise weapon with interesting possibilities. } *